HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 998
By Salinas
A RESOLUTION to recognize and honor St. Agnes Academy on
the occasion of its 175th anniversary.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly are proud to recognize those
hallowed educational institutions that are celebrating momentous occasions in their long and
storied histories; and
WHEREAS, St. Agnes Academy of Memphis is one such distinguished institution that is
celebrating its 175th anniversary in 2026; and
WHEREAS, in 1851, six Dominican Sisters from Kentucky arrived in Memphis on
January 1st to establish a school for girls, and St. Agnes Female Academy opened one month
later with day and boarding students; and
WHEREAS, the Academy was originally located at Vance and Orleans, which was then
in a suburb of Memphis; enrollment grew rapidly in its first year, exceeding fifty students and
prompting immediate expansion of the original building; and
WHEREAS, throughout its history, the Dominican Sisters persevered through
extraordinary hardships, including ministering to wounded soldiers during the Civil War,
enduring yellow fever epidemics in 1867, 1873, and 1878, and rebuilding after devastating fires
in 1878 and 1900, yet the school never closed—a testament to the resilience of its founders and
the enduring strength of its mission; and
WHEREAS, St. Agnes Academy continued to grow and thrive, adding new wings in
1911, establishing The Memphis Conservatory of Music in 1918 as a major center for formal
music education in the city, and relocating in 1951 to its current campus on Walnut Grove Road
after a century of educating young women in Memphis; and
